### Modeling and Predicting Human Mobility Patterns: A Data-Driven Approach

This project focused on modeling and predicting large-scale human mobility patterns by analyzing population flow data across different geographic regions. Using weekly mobility data spanning the COVID-19 timeline, the goal was to understand and predict how group-level movement patterns evolved over time under changing real-world conditions.

**Technical Context**: CMSE 202 — Computational Modeling Tools and Techniques

**Dataset + Data Handling**  
The project used the publicly available [COVID19USFlows – Weekly Flows](https://github.com/GeoDS/COVID19USFlows-WeeklyFlows/tree/master) dataset. Weekly CSV updates were aggregated and processed using Pandas, then split into training (January 2019 – June 2021) and testing (July 2021 – December 2021) datasets to enable forward-looking prediction.

**Methodology**
- Preprocessed and combined large-scale CSV datasets representing population flows between geographic regions.
- Trained two regression-based machine learning models:
  - Random Forest Regression
  - Gradient Boosting Regression
- Evaluated model performance by comparing predicted flows against held-out test data.
- Analyzed relative error to assess predictive accuracy and model robustness.

**Performance**
- **Random Forest Regression**: Relative error of approximately **0.04%**, demonstrating strong predictive performance.
- **Gradient Boosting Regression**: Relative error of approximately **163.95%**, indicating sensitivity to data anomalies and poorer generalization.

**Further Thoughts**
Potential improvements include exploring neural network–based models to better handle non-linearities and anomalous events in the data. Additionally, filtering or explicitly modeling disruptions caused by holidays, large events, or natural disasters could improve predictive stability.
